2  B
Mismatch detected.
3. Partition Level Validation (Very Important)
Since your table is partitioned on report_date, validate partition data.
Example:
SQL
Copy code
SELECT report_date, COUNT(*) 
FROM dbo.cff_report
GROUP BY report_date
ORDER BY report_date
Compare with:
SQL
Copy code
SELECT report_date, COUNT(*) 
FROM dbo.cff_report_new
GROUP BY report_date
ORDER BY report_date
This ensures each partition copied correctly.
4. Using CHECKSUM (Fast Validation)
For very large tables like 50M rows, EXCEPT may be expensive.
Use CHECKSUM aggregation.
Old table:
SQL
Copy code
SELECT CHECKSUM_AGG(BINARY_CHECKSUM(*))
FROM dbo.cff_report
New table:
SQL
Copy code
SELECT CHECKSUM_AGG(BINARY_CHECKSUM(*))
FROM dbo.cff_report_new
If checksum values match, data is very likely identical.
Example:
Plain text
Copy code
Old checksum = 23892783
New checksum = 23892783
5. Partition Checksum (Best for Large Tables)
Validate partition by partition.
SQL
Copy code
SELECT 
report_date,
COUNT(*) row_count,
CHECKSUM_AGG(BINARY_CHECKSUM(*)) checksum_val
FROM dbo.cff_report
GROUP BY report_date
Compare with new table:
SQL
Copy code
SELECT 
report_date,
COUNT(*) row_count,
CHECKSUM_AGG(BINARY_CHECKSUM(*)) checksum_val
FROM dbo.cff_report_new
GROUP BY report_date
This gives very strong validation.
6. Detect Exact Row Differences
Best query to find exact mismatch.
SQL
Copy code
SELECT *
FROM dbo.cff_report o
FULL OUTER JOIN dbo.cff_report_new n
ON o.primary_key = n.primary_key
WHERE
o.primary_key IS NULL
OR n.primary_key IS NULL
OR EXISTS
(
SELECT o.*
EXCEPT
SELECT n.*
)
This shows rows where data changed.
